Text.Value: You don't understand. You've been an idol of mine for years.
Now - lead on.
You're sure?
When we cannot know, we can only trust. But then, that is exactly what a traitor in our midst would say - isn't it?
Nothing happens in this city that she doesn't hear of, sooner or later.
Thank you, Jaheira. That would be fantastic.
Farewell.
I believe you have an appointment with a Netherbrain.
*Nine-Fingers. As a child, your father spoke her name in anxious whispers. She runs the Guild - which in turn runs every criminal enterprise in the city.*
Minsc certainly made his home in that hideout - but he's up to something somewhere else.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: I'll definitely need to revisit this for a flag later - For now if you use the debug book to teleport to the Abandoned Cistern interior and haven't done the robbery scene, it should be accessible

Text.Value: I do.
She is no one to be trifled with.
Congratulations are in order. I fancied myself the sage advisor, sworn to guide you through what it means to be a child of Bhaal.
Try not to pass out.
See if you still feel the same afterwards.

EditorData.NodeContext: being tough but with warmth underneath it.

Text.Value: Are you... well? You have a rather vacant, tadpole-finally-ate-my-brain look about you.
There's something else I wanted to discuss.
Ah. The guildmaster wishes to see us, does she? Better we call on her home than she call on ours. Lead, then.
Yes?
Jaheira, ma'am, I can't tell you what it means to me to be working together.
Perhaps it is uncouth to have taken pleasure in that. I am content to be uncouth.
Join me.
Huh. Not so much a term of age or affection as simple old habit. You object?
That was horrible.
We need to part ways for the moment. I'll see you back here.
Now now - I need a moment.
But whatever your feelings on Nine-Fingers - whatever mine - I cannot see how we served the city by putting the Zhentarim in her place.
We could. It would just be a very short one.
Nine-Fingers Keene controls the Guild, which in turn controls every criminal racket from Heapside to the High Hall.
Ah. I know that one. They say I turned the very blades of grass against her. Her staff of office leapt into my hand, naming me its rightful wielder.
She runs the Guild. Which itself runs every criminal enterprise in the city.
Always.
Information. The Chosen have a head start on us - I'd like to know what they've done with it.
Tell her what happened at the Harper safe-house.
Have you thought any more about how we might find Minsc?
And will be again. But now I shall mutter them under my breath, out of respect.
What are you hoping to find there, again?
Look alive, girl! Recall our arrangement - I give the orders, you do all the work.
You mentioned there might be another way to find Minsc.
Good. Ketheric thought he was safe, too.
I asked for your help. Set us on course for what happened at the Guildhall. So perhaps I have no right to question.
'Friend' is not the word I'd use. Nor is 'petty', if you've a mind to keep your tongue.

EditorData.NodeContext: Warning us not to dismiss Nine-Fingers

Text.Value: How hospitable she will be to a Harper that comes begging to her Guildhall... we will find out. Perhaps I will let you do the talking.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not relishing the idea of walking into an enemy's lair.

Text.Value: Indeed.
These days, they have nothing but the Stone Lord to talk about.
As you like. No cub, no fun.
The Harpers are the city's best information network. With them out of action, we shall have to fall back on second-best.

EditorData.NodeContext: Jaheira's Harpers have been infiltrated, she can't use them.

Text.Value: But if you insist on calling me ma'am, I'll happily snap a few orders while you do all the work?

EditorData.NodeContext: wryly, she's kidding here but playing it tough

Text.Value: Still, if you see sense in making an alliance, I won't question it. I'll just look forward to the inevitable breaking Gortash spoke of.
Of course. You're no true Baldurian unless you've sloshed around in the slurry, after all.
We cannot expect either of the Chosen to fall easily. But fall they must, if we're to have all three stones to command the brain.
I didn't think a Harper would be friends with a petty crime lord.
I ought to be saying that to you, girl. Only one of us here clawed her way free of the Hells themselves.
That instinct is what allowed our alliance to endure so long as it did - that she could place her personal feelings aside, and do what she thought best for the city.
*A name known, and feared, throughout the city's underworld. The mysterious Keene runs the Guild - which in turn runs every criminal enterprise in the city.*
And while I mulled on that solemn responsibility - you went and took care of it on your own.
One cannot embrace a viper - only get entangled by it.
Let it wait until the city proper. Perhaps I'll have had a better idea by then.
You know enough. And so do I.

EditorData.NodeContext: She dislikes the player - tone is making it clear we work together, but not to expect more than that.

Text.Value: What.

EditorData.NodeContext: Flat, disinterested - this is a greeting specifically if we've pissed her off for any reason, and she's not inclined to chitchat.

Text.Value: I am.
And what do you think of his warning - of the doppelganger in our camp?
I look forward to the day we show the Archduke that his tongue is not half so silvered as he thinks.
Why didn't you tell me about your family?
Is it true you once out-spelled an eladrin druid in her own grove?
Leave idols to the druids - we already tie ourselves in knots over them. Let me be your follower instead. Your friend, even.
I wonder if Gortash knows just who it is he is dealing with.
Jaheira, ma'am, I can't tell you what it means to me to be working together.
Leave.
You're not interested in his offer?
Ah. I know what she speaks of. I need... information from her. And a pardon from you - for I have not been overly generous with the truth.
Leave.
And now it is Gortash's turn. We'll need his stone to finish this - however you plan to acquire it. So let us go pay Lord Liar a visit.
A Harper learns to doubt. To peer through every smile, question every look. Eventually you find whatever it is you fear, whether it is there or not.
Not so long as I get to call you crow.
There might be, but... it is not a path I'd tread until we must.
You have a history with Sarevok.
Pfft. Do not feign smallness, girl - it doesn't suit you. I am the follower here. Though I would ask we keep the jumping to a minimum.
Stlarning shapechangers. And of course the fool would follow their every word, just because they wear my face.
You say that like it should mean something.
As do I - but we agreed to deal with Orin first.
Ask it.
Of course. He'll share his rule - what use all his brilliance, if there is no one to bask in it?
Well done. Truly.
As do you, now. And all our hands are stained by association. I can see the greater good in it, should it lead us to Orin.
'The Cub and the Crow' - sounds like a cautionary tale. As it probably should.
Perhaps.
A true pleasure, to watch you tell the Archduke exactly where to put his alliance.
I'm sorry, Jaheira. I know she was your friend - but the city is better off without her.
Later, then. I'd tell you not to get in trouble, but I suspect it will find you whether you like it or not.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not offended - tweaking our noses a bit, but tone is mild

Text.Value: Tell her about the encounter with Nine-Fingers.
We can't pick a fight while he's surrounded by his Steel Watch.
Amble about if you wish. I plan to claim whatever little rest remains.
We need to part ways for the moment. I'll find you at camp.
To which we've added a low and craven chapter. I can see the greater good in it, should it lead us to Orin.
He seems more cooperative than Orin, at least.
I think Minsc might have fled down into the sewers.
The cub speaks.
Watching gods, but I never thought I would be happy to see this city again. Much less to smell it.

EditorData.NodeContext: Looking around at the city in which's spent most of her life - unintentionally. She's a druid, and would rather be out in the wilds - but this is still her home.

Text.Value: Nine-Fingers Keene.
So it seems I must honour that, and do the same. But mark my words: when the Absolute is finished, when all of this is done - the city will feel her loss.
Are you forgetting that she wanted Minsc dead?
But both our operations step outside the law when needful. She just likes it better there.
Actually, never mind.
We are a little ways from our camp here. You'll just have to put up with me, for now.
It would be irritatingly true to form, would it not?
I have. And while I do not love my conclusion, that does nothing to change it.
Where do you suggest we begin?
I would be lying if I told you I was certain we would walk out of that temple alive.
Oh, so kind. And so naive.

EditorData.NodeContext: being tough but with warmth underneath it.

Text.Value: Care to discuss that scroll of yours?
Nothing so grand. He was just another broken little Bhaalspawn, who tried to clamber to glory over the corpses of others.
Let us speak later.
You're right. You have no right to question.
Well done indeed! Though now you will never see a god of death cower before a miniature giant space hamster. Every choice has a cost, I suppose.
But you found your footing where so many before you have fallen. Wherever you lead from now, we will follow.
Sounds like a tavern game.
But he slunk back into his father's shadow instead. There is nothing more to say of him.
I'd be too terrified of accidentally hurting the Jaheira.
Nine-Fingers is much more than a thief. Nothing happens in this city that she doesn't learn of, sooner or later.
That was amazing.
But if you need proof that I am flesh and blood, Karlach, and none the fresher for it - perhaps we might train together at camp.
Close. When I realised she was far the better mage, I snatched it from her and used it for a club. I fear I do not live up to campfire tales.
Back and forth. You're like to make me dizzy.

EditorData.NodeContext: wry "these young folk are so changeable"

Text.Value: There's little point in pressing Nine-Fingers further. She means what she says.
A fine thing, to travel in a small pack once more. No doubt Ketheric thinks he has escaped us.
But her every act, even those I opposed, was done in service to her city. No matter her personal feelings.
If it does not, you have led a very virtuous life indeed.

EditorData.NodeContext: Surprised we haven't heard of a big crime boss she named - Nine-Fingers

Text.Value: What is it?
Speak, so long as you have something sensible to say.
The Guild? You'd throw your lot in with thieves?
Astele did not have whims. She was a criminal, yes. Even a brute, when she had to be.
Never.
Oh, to be so innocent.

EditorData.NodeContext: Surprised we haven't heard of a big crime boss she named - Nine-Fingers

Text.Value: What is it, cub?
To work together? Strangely enough, I believe him - he's too self-important to be anything but sincere.
I wanted to ask you something.
Simple. The Zhentarim follow gold - not the whims of any guildmaster.
Well. You, and a certain miniature giant space hamster. But mostly you, true.
He's protected by his Steel Watch for now - and Orin will have her own defences, should we choose to play the part of Gortash's bloodhounds.
I've been called worse things.
Speak.
We faced Bhaal there once before, and I was not ready to count on luck a second time. But luck had no part in it - just you.
As do I.
Yes?
But we swore no vows. She won't tell us where to find Minsc, someone else in her Guildhall will. We need to be swift.
I have no illusions about who Astele was. She was a criminal. A brute, even, when she had to be.
Fine with me. As far as I'm concerned, you say 'jump' and I say 'how high'.
The great Archduke's coronation became his funeral rite. At least the flowers will not go to waste.
But even if we unite to command the brain, it's not as if we can leave the city under Bane's boot-heel once it's done. We'd be back to the same old battle.
I need to think a while.
The path of a Bhaalspawn is not an easy one - nor does it ever truly end.
Well - first things first, I owe you an apology. I did not tell you of all I hoped to find in the city.
What.
The Undercity is perilous, but I recall Minsc making a home down there in the old days. 'To plant his boot on the very bosom of evil', or some such.
As you wish.
One final night in the open air, and then back to the city. Rest while you can - I fear that quite a bit of work awaits us.
I'm fine. Let's keep moving.
I shall be content with that. For now.
But he slunk back into his father's shadow instead. Let him be a cautionary tale to you - your father will only love you so long as he can use you.

EditorData.logicalname: LOGIC - Only here to set the flag to end the dialog and avoid an error

Text.Value: You have enough fine young folk to run around and do your bidding. Come back when they need a rest.
I suppose we must greet the local wild-life. The Guildhall is awash with ale-scented gossip at the best of times.
I found a strange scroll in your sanctuary. Something about a 'timeless body'?
Nor are we. But I trust she knows the value of collaboration, especially in times like these.

EditorData.NodeContext: Rationalising her willingess to deal with a crime lord.

Text.Value: I would not linger in this land overlong. But - whatever your business, I will aid you if I can.
We didn't. The city's free of the Zhentarim - and now the guildmaster's whims, too.
I'll mark an entrance I know - from there, we shall just have to follow our noses.
Now we're travelling together, I realise I don't know much about you.
Well - are we ready for the road once more?

EditorData.NodeContext: Neutral to positive, general slice-of-life greetings in camp.

Text.Value: I've had a lifetime's fill of watching little men puff themselves up with grand titles.

EditorData.logicalname: Post Gortash, no answer on deal.

Text.Value: And we learned something. One Chosen thinks to send us against the other, while they sit safe behind their defences.
That is both Chosen beaten, and their stones wrested from their grasp. But where they fall, the elder brain rises.
Nine-Fingers - a name that could make a city guard tremble. If they aren't already on her payroll, that is.
...As you say, then. My friend is saved, and we have another ally in the fight against the Absolute.
We need all three stones to command the brain. It matters little in what order we obtain them, or how.
Now is not the best moment to leave. You'll just have to put up with me, for now.

EditorData.logicalname: Logic node: Wyll did not speak inclusion

Text.Value: How are you faring without your Harpers?
I met your family. Rion is rather keen to see you.
But you found your footing where so many before you have fallen. Wherever you lead from now, we will follow.
Lead, then. Nature's servant awaits.
The Harper safe-house I spoke of is on the bridge at Wyrm's Crossing - Danthelon's Dancing Axe.
That speaks well of your taste. I've heard my share of bad ballads about things I never did.

EditorData.NodeContext: Happy that we don't know much about her. Not a big fan of her fame - she has work to do.

Text.Value: No.
Yes.
There was a time when he might have made more of himself - he was certainly given the chance, after we threw him down.
You're the boss.
Tell her about what happened at the Counting House.
Fools. As if the promise of any amount of gold would make them Dame Aylin's equal.
It is already worming its way free. We must find it before it slips its collar, whether we are ready or not.

Synopsis: Jaheira's default dialogue. Topics range from her past life to her current goals as they develop. Unless otherwise stated, her tone is confident and to the point. She's a seasoned adventurer with a sardonic sense of humour - and a little less cynical than she might present herself to be.
